<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-588-447  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 588 447.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Design  May 1 1989 v28 n9 p77(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Ada tools mature, but users debate language standards. (includesrelated article on Ada's standard features) (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Falk, Howard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Ada language has a reputation for awkward, primitive tools,but now more adequate tools are available.andP;  Also, debuggers likethose for C language can be found.andP;  Ada vendors are looking forimproved software products for real-time and embedded systems.andO;One main requirement of embedded systems is that the software musttake up as little target memory space as possible.andP;  Today's Adacompiler only loads those run-time features needed by theapplication being used.andP;  Few people know that a new version of theAda language will officially be adopted sometime in the 1990s.andO;The main issue being discussed among standard makers is how tocorrect some of the snarls that make Ada difficult to use.andP;  Someargue that there should be only minimal changes in the Adalanguage, since Ada is a standard language by definition.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ADAReal-Time SystemsDistributed SystemsProgramming LanguagesStandardsDebuggingCompilersProgram Development ToolsUpgradingUser SurveyTechnology.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   The RTAda run-time system. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>